@@yThe Great Oasis — The Deepwell Confluence@@N

@@eBefore any dynasty carved a pyramid block, the Great Oasis already existed:
a confluence of three underground springs rising through fractured limestone
into a shallow basin. The earliest name for this site, preserved on
pre-dynastic clay seals, is the Deepwell Confluence. Every caravan route in
the eastern waste converged upon it, for it was the only reliable year-round
water source within six days' travel in any direction.@@N

@@dThe Keepers of Measure built the world's first hydraulic regulation system
here: the Cistern Ring. Four underground chambers arranged in a ring below
the basin governed daily distribution, drought emergency, caravan provisioning,
and agricultural irrigation. The four sluice masters who controlled these
chambers formed the Water Court, the earliest governing body in the desert.@@N

@@yAbove the cisterns stood the Measuring House, aligned to true cardinal within
a thumb-width. Its narrow roof apertures allowed sunlight to fall on
calibration marks at precise times. All road alignments and survey calculations
across the eastern desert were calibrated against its central gnomon stone.@@N

@@eThe Waystone Circle, twelve upright limestone slabs, ringed the oasis. Each
bore the Charter of Passage, encoding directional glyphs and legal formulae
in Measure Script. Every road in the desert began and ended with reference
to these stones.@@N

@@dThe Salt Ledger Kingdoms later raised a Toll Pavilion atop the ruined
Measuring House. The High Water Court became supreme arbiter for water-right
disputes across the entire road network. Garden terraces were built at the
margins, tended by the hereditary Reed Tenders caste.@@N

@@rThe oasis's springs have diminished since the Iseth Reach dried, a
consequence of drought and the Ninth Meridian Rite's catastrophic failure.
But the Cistern Ring still functions, and the Water Court's legal formulae
still govern desert trade. The heart of the corridor's water law beats here
yet.@@N
